programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: Throughout his career, throwing a no-hitter was one accolade that had eluded Hall of Famer Tom Seaver. There were many close calls and one-hitters, but finally on June 16, 1978, Tom Terrific made history with the Reds and kept the Cardinals hitless.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/14/79: In a pivotal Game 5, the Pirates score seven runs late in the game. Jim Rooker and Bert Blyleven throw a one-run game starting the Pirates' comeback in the 1979 World Series.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/17/79: After falling behind 3-1 in the 1979 World Series, the Pirates rallied to come back and take home a championship. Willie Stargell goes 4-for-5 with a home run in Game 7 to lift the Pirates to a 4-1 win over the Orioles.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/21/80: Tug McGraw strikes out Willie Wilson on a 1-2 fastball in Game 6 sealing the Phillies' 4-1 win over the Royals, bringing home the franchise's first-ever World Series Championship.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/20/82: With the championship on the line, Bruce Sutter comes into the game in the 8th inning to blank the Brewers. The Cardinals captured their ninth World Series win in a dramatic Game 7 win at Busch Stadium.

programme.title: Great Games
programme.desc: 10/10/1982 - Cecil Cooper plates a pair of runs on a go-ahead single in the bottom 7th inning and the Brewers hold on to secure a 4-3 win over the Angels, punching their ticket to the 1982 World Series.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Remote Cities
programme.desc: Brave the frontiers of the world’s most remote cities. More than distant trading posts and isolated regional hubs, cities like Alice Springs, Jaipur and even Las Vegas serve as gateways to the wild places of the Earth.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Rivers
programme.desc: Rivers flow freely - beautiful and powerful waterways that underscore the melody of life. As they meander through the landscape, they shape it, wearing down ranges and deepening valleys, eventually flowing out into the sea.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Volcanoes
programme.desc: There are few sights on earth as compelling as a volcanic eruption. Volcanoes have the potential to cause death and widespread destruction in a heartbeat, but they also give rise to new life and ecosystems.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Archipelagos
programme.desc: The romantic notion of island life has always attracted us. Explore the histories, cultures, and unique ways of life on the World’s Greatest Archipelagos - clusters of islands that share common bonds of geography, geology, and genealogy.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Island Nations
programme.desc: Though many are small in stature, they have punched well above their weight on the global stage. Some are rooted in ancient history, while others are only just beginning to realize their full potential.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Lost Cities
programme.desc: Once powerful and populous centers of influence, these lost cities are providing clues to how our ancestors existed in the world and remind us that ancient civilizations were not so far removed from our own.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Extreme Animals
programme.desc: Extreme Animals features environments hostile to humans, but havens to many animals. Witness gorgeous glow-worms, high flying condors, parched thorny devils, emperor penguins, and polar bears in this journey through life on the edge.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Land Adventures
programme.desc: Most land adventures come with some risk - a chance to confront our deepest fears, resist the pull of the ordinary, and soar into the wild unknown.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Capital Cities
programme.desc: With visionaries, politicians, and activists, these metropolises are defined as the official seats of government. Dublin, Washington, and Taipei share broad avenues, museums, and monuments, but are as varied as the countries they represent.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Mega Cities
programme.desc: Mega Cities provide a bustling home to populations of over 10 million. Travel from the high-density living of Shanghai and Bangkok to the sprawling cities of Delhi and Mexico City, each the backdrop for dynamic cultures.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Grassland Animals
programme.desc: Grasslands are the great stages of the natural world where large animals play out spectacular lives in clear view of people, including lions, leopards, elephants, rhinoceros, cheetahs, impalas, kangaroos, wallaby, potoroo, bison, and wolves.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Island Arks
programme.desc: Cut off from continents, remote islands have become floating arks, attracting migrating species and forging new ones. Take a privileged glimpse into the secret lives of the rare and exotic species that inhabit these lost worlds.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Sacred Sites
programme.desc: Ancient in architecture and detailed in design, these man-made masterpieces stand as testaments to the strength of human faith. These sites endure as a timeless reminder of resilience, respect, and the need to reflect.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Water Adventures
programme.desc: We are captivated by oceans, rivers, and lakes - the power, the flow, the reflective stillness. And as we seek to get closer, we immerse ourselves in an expanding range of aquatic experiences.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Coasts
programme.desc: Along coasts, one element ends and another begins. No two days are ever the same on a coastline: the only thing that remains a constant is the timeless power of the sea.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Forest Animals
programme.desc: Forest Animals gets up close with bears, koalas, moose, wolves, weaver ants, and Tasmanian Devils. This episode roves dark forests floors and soars above vast canopies of green in America, China, Laos, and Australia.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Coral Islands
programme.desc: The reef systems that gave rise to coral islands support the vast majority of marine species on our planet, but they are under threat. Explore the delicate balance between exploiting and preserving these extraordinary natural wonders.

programme.title: Tony Robinson's VE Day: Minute by Minute
programme.desc: Take a unique look at a pivotal day in the history of the modern world, delving into the key events that made VE Day such a momentous 24 hours.

programme.title: Voices of D-Day Landings
programme.desc: In the early hours of June 6th, 1944 Allied forces began the greatest military assault ever attempted. They came to Normandy by both air and sea with one objective.

programme.title: The Ultimate History of the Messerschmitt
programme.desc: In this program we look at the development of the Bf 109 which flew in all theaters of conflict in which the Luftwaffe was involved. More Bf 109s were built than any other fighter of the era.

programme.title: NEW: The Siege of Malta
programme.desc: At last here is the definitive story of heroism and hardship of a people uniquely and collectively awarded the George Cross 'for gallantry', and told by some of the heroic survivors.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: The battles of the first world war were battles of attrition and trenches; the battles of the second world war were vastly different. In this episode we study tank battles, blitzkrieg, commando raids, amphibious landings, and mobile warfare in the desert.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: The second world war was conflict on an unprecedented scale. Its battles set new marks for the sheer size of forces deployed and for the power of their weapons. In this episode we study the first battle at sea, and the largest army to have ever marched.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: A war that reached every continent and touched every sort of terrain demanded every sort of strategy. In this episode we examine battles fought at sea, and in the jungle, in city streets, invasions from the air, and retreats from the land.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Battles are almost always about territory. Advancing the front line, seizing the port, the city, the oil field. The fate of nations in the war rose and fell on battles that took territory. Singapore, Monte Casino, Stalingrad...all about territory.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Every war seized new tactics; some inspired, some desperate, all attempting to influence the course of battles. Campaigns waged against non military targets to demoralize. Suicide missions launched when traditional weapons failed. Rules were rewritten.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: A world war is a patchwork of actions. Land. Sea. Air. Massive, or small scale. The stories of these actions, are just as varied. This episode describes battles of amphibious forces, climate, geography, and the problems of supply.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Through history, armies marched to face each other on favored ground and clashed to decide a campaign, a war, an empire. With the 20th century that changed. The battles of the WWII happened anywhere and everywhere, in every weather and climate.

programme.title: World War II: Battles Won and Lost
programme.desc: Some words transcend their origins as humble place names. They are carved into history as turning points which influenced the course of WWII, the fate of nations, and the make-up of our world. El Alameine, Okinawa, and Pearl Harbor.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Aristocrat and the Balkan Communists
programme.desc: Fitzroy Maclean, an MP and WWII spy, supported Tito's Communist partisans in Yugoslavia against the Germans, forging a lasting friendship and honored at Tito's funeral post-war.
programme.sub-title: The Aristocrat and the Balkan Communists

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Agent Garbo
programme.desc: Juan Pujol, MI6's WWII agent "Garbo," created a fictitious spy network in Lisbon, deceiving the Germans with crucial disinformation and influencing their strategies. After the war, MI6 protected him, and he lived in Venezuela until his death in 1988.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Christine Granville
programme.desc: Christine Granville, aka Krystyna Skarbek, a brave SOE agent, secured the release of captured comrades from the Gestapo before Operation Dragoon, earning the George Medal.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The French Triple Agent
programme.desc: Operation Cockade, led by MI6's double agent Henri Dericourt in 1943, aimed to deceive Germans with sabotage. Despite efforts, Germans withdrew divisions unconvinced. Dericourt faced a post-war treason trial and died in a mysterious 1962 plane crash.

programme.title: Einsatzgruppen: The Nazi Death Squads: Time Of Reckoning
programme.desc: After being judged at the Nuremberg trials, the majority of those responsible for the murder of nearly 1.5 million Jews would walk free in the 1950s

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: X-Rated
programme.desc: Adolf Hitler had a depraved sex life that he tried to keep hidden from the German public. He was said to be a chronic masturbator, a voyeur and that he engaged in sado-masochistic sex with women.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: Body Image
programme.desc: Hitler wanted the world to believe he possessed super-human qualities but in private he was a wreck. This episode reveals the archives that confirm Hitler’s genital deformity, the alarming truth about his heavy drug addiction and the Parkinson’s.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: Family Matters
programme.desc: Adolf Hitler's father was a violent, abusive man. His mother doted on her young son. This episode delves deep into the psychology of Hitler as the narcissistic child who grew into a malignant psychopath full of rage and deep hatred.

programme.title: Hitler's Secret Sex Life: Suicidal Maidens
programme.desc: Using extensive archival research, this program explores the squalid secrets he lied and killed to protect

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Seeds of Violence 1918-1922
programme.desc: The Seeds of Violence 1918-1922: In the wake of the First World War, Adolf Hitler identifies Benito Mussolini as his model and has one ultimate goal: to gain power in Germany.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Deceit and Delusion 1923-1928
programme.desc: Deceit and Delusion 1923-1928: Hitler appears to be eliminated after his failed putsch in 1923. Discover how the Nazi movement used democracy's tolerance in Germany to come back.

programme.desc: Deceit and Delusion 1923-1928: Hitler appears to be eliminated after his failed putsch in 1923. Discover how the Nazi movement used democracy's tolerance in Germany to come back.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Democracy without Democrats 1929-1933
programme.desc: Democracy Without Democrats 1929-1933: A protest turns into a racist and anti-Jewish movement during the 1920s and the NSDAP use emotions to gain the loyalty of the people.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Racial State 1933-1934
programme.desc: The Racial State 1933-1934: President Hindenburg suspends freedom of speech and Hitler comes to power in 1933. The first concentration camps for political opponents are set up.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Hidden in Plain Sight 1935-1938
programme.desc: Hidden In Plain Sight 1935-1938: In 1934, Hitler's government is firmly in the saddle. Most Germans support Hitler's anti-Jewish policy and the regime's terror soon escalates.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Up in Flames 1936-1940
programme.desc: Up in Flames 1936-1940: At the end of 1939, the German Army invades Poland. Examine how Hitler succeeded in pushing through his rearmament and war plans relatively unhindered.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Gates of Hell 1941-1942
programme.desc: The Gates of Hell 1941-1942: In the shadow of the war, the Nazi regime gradually advances its "final solution to the Jewish problem", culminating in the Holocaust.

programme.title: Britain's Greatest Bridges: The Britannia Bridge

programme.title: Britain's Greatest Bridges: The Forth Rail Bridge

programme.title: Building Britain's Canals: Kennet and Avon

programme.title: Building Britain's Canals: Grand Union Canal

programme.title: Building Britain's Canals: Leeds & Liverpool Canal

programme.title: Giant Constructions: Moving Bridges

programme.title: Giant Constructions: Steel Bridges
programme.desc: Steel bridges are extremely durable and multifunctional, fascinating not only due to its gigantic size but also because of the army of workers keeping the bridges in shape: whether on the historical landmark in Sydney or ultramodern mega bridges in China.

programme.title: Giant Constructions: Railway Bridges

programme.title: Giant Constructions: Road Bridges

programme.title: Giant Constructions: Suspension Bridges
programme.desc: Suspension bridges – impressively wide and stretched high over supporting cables or stay cables. The landscape-shaping icons: The superlative Golden Gate, Akashi Kaikyo, Aizaih, El Baluarte and Russky Bridge.

programme.title: Mega Transports: Biggest Containership
programme.desc: When the first ship of the brand-new OOCL-fleet gets underway, more cargo is moved at one time than anywhere else in the world and ever before.

programme.title: Mega Transports: Drilling Rig

programme.title: Mega Transports: ITER Magnet
programme.desc: This giant magnet will revolutionize the world and energy production in the future. The world's largest nuclear fusion reactor is currently under construction in southern France.

programme.title: Mega Transports: Giant Antenna

programme.title: Mega Transports: Conveyance of the Norwegian Joy

programme.title: Mega Transports: Superyachts
programme.desc: Transporting a ship by a ship - this becomes necessary when the super-rich want their super yacht available on the other side of the world, but do not want to sail it there themselves.

programme.title: Mega Transports: AutoClav
programme.desc: A unique mega transport made of steel and titanium with a special purpose: to extract tons of gold. This so-called autoclave is the biggest of its kind. Its weight: over one thousand tons.

programme.title: Mega Transports: Villagemove

programme.title: 48 Hours: Murder in L.A.
programme.desc: Focuses on two California couples: the Adairs and the Shapiros. Mindy Shapiro discovered that her husband Michael, an orthopedic surgeon, was having an affair with Jeanie Adair, and in 1996, after 11 years of marriage, the couple opted for divorce.

programme.title: 48 Hours: The Enemy Within
programme.desc: An investigation of the murder of Vicki Robinson, a 49-year-old divorced Florida real estate agent, and the role of her 15-year-old daughter, Valessa in the crime.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Heroes Under Fire
programme.desc: A fire that ignited in an abandoned warehouse in Worcester, Massachusetts in 1999, claimed the lives of six firefighters. A homeless couple living in the building, were subsequently charged with manslaughter for starting the blaze.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Citizen Jane
programme.desc: When Gertrude McCabe was murdered, her niece Jane Alexander was named her principal beneficiary. Jane, a widow in her 70s, began to suspect that her live-in boyfriend, Tom O'Donnell, might have been involved in the crime.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Daddy's Little Girl
programme.desc: At 16 Mindy Berenyi, an Antwerp, Ohio girl claiming to be a victim of physical and psychological abuse, was tried for the murder of her father and, having agreed to a plea bargain, was sentenced to prison.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Accused
programme.desc: In 1996 the car which Sheila Bryan was driving with her mother as passenger accidentally veered off the road and into a ditch killing her mother. Sheila was charged with murder -- then tried, convicted, and sentenced to life imprisonment.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Ghosts of Mississippi
programme.desc: A report on a string of unsolved homicides in Columbus, Mississippi. Five elderly residents, all living within a mile of each other, were killed within 18 months. Police say, a terrified community believes a serial killer is on the loose.

programme.title: 48 Hours
programme.desc: Elizabeth Welsh's husband, Patrick, left her and their two sons what appeared to be a suicide note and disappeared. After investigating the situation, Elizabeth discovered that Patrick is still alive, living in Texas.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Getting Away with Murder?
programme.desc: A report on families who have experienced the violent death of a loved one and believe they know the identity of the killer but lack evidence to back the charge.

programme.title: 48 Hours: A Mother Accused
programme.desc: This report investigates alleged incidents of Shaken Baby Syndrome, focusing on accusations involving Paulette and Kelly Welch, a Mormon couple living in Idaho Falls, Idaho, whose adopted son Stockton died on May 1, 1999 following a fall in their home.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Murder in Spokane
programme.desc: A report that focuses on the murders in Spokane, Washington over a period of a little more than two years (1997 - 1999) of at least a dozen women, mostly prostitutes.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Murder They Wrote: The End of the Dream
programme.desc: A report on the charismatic Scott Scurlock, known as “Hollywood” because of his flamboyant style and effective use of disguises in the commission of crimes, successfully eluded capture for four years while effortlessly robbing 18 banks.
programme.sub-title: Murder They Wrote: The End of the Dream

programme.title: 48 Hours: A Cop Behind Bars
programme.desc: Patrick Bradford, was convicted of stabbing his mistress to death. Determined to win his acquittal, Deborah Nolan, a close friend, and staunch supporter of Bradford’s, quit her teaching job and went to law school to take on his defense.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Murder in Las Vegas
programme.desc: Ron Rudin, a wealthy real-estate developer disappeared from his home in Las Vegas, Nev. Later, the charred remains of his decapitated body were found in the desert. After a lengthy investigation police were convinced that Rudin’s wife was involved.

programme.title: 48 Hours: A Family Torn Apart
programme.desc: The murdered body of Bob Dorotik, a engineer and father of three, was found by a mountain road near his home in the foothills of San Diego, Ca. Despite her denial of any involvement, Jane, Dorotik’s wife of 30 years, was arrested for the crime.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Double Jeopardy
programme.desc: The investigation of the September 24, 1988 sexual torture-murder in Louisville, Kentucky, of Brenda Sue Schaefer.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Fatal Attraction
programme.desc: Thomas Capano, a successful Delaware lawyer lived a double life, a devoted family man while having affairs. When Anne Marie Fahey, one of these women, mysteriously disappeared police were at first stumped. Finally evidence led to Capano.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Bitter Pill
programme.desc: Stella Nickell of Auburn, Washington, was sentenced to 90 year in federal prison for poisoning her husband Bruce and Sue Snow, a Seattle bank manager with cyanide-laced Excedrin.

programme.title: 48 Hours: The Mystery of Slide Mountain
programme.desc: A report that examines evidence and unanswered questions regarding a June 1, 1998 auto accident on Slide Mountain, near Reno, Nevada, that led to the death of Rinette Riella Bergna and left the driver, Rinette’s husband Peter with only minor injuries.

programme.title: 48 Hours: The Colonel's Wife
programme.desc: Ret. Col. George Maracek, a 69-year-old former Green Beret who served in Korea and Vietnam, has been charged with the 1991 murder of his Thai wife Viparet. He maintains that he is innocent.

programme.title: Spycraft
programme.desc: Intelligence officers acquire the information collected by sources, from old-school "dead drops" to high-tech digital transfers.

programme.title: Royal Murder Mysteries
programme.desc: Exploring new clues that put the murder of Russian princess, Anastasia, in doubt.

programme.title: Forbidden History
programme.desc: Investigating a theory suggesting that Hitler did not kill himself at the end of World War II, but escaped to Argentina to live out the rest of his life in the foothills of Patagonia with his wife Eva Braun.

programme.title: Forbidden History
programme.desc: Investigating the identity of the Man in the Iron Mask, a nameless prisoner under Louis XIV.
programme.sub-title: The Man in the Iron Mask

programme.title: History's Greatest Hoaxes
programme.desc: The apparent discovery of Hitler's diaries in 1983 caused a sensation, but they were fake.

programme.title: Royal Murder Mysteries
programme.desc: Testing the rumors of a connection between an English prince and Jack the Ripper.
programme.sub-title: Albert Victor: The Prince and the Ripper

programme.title: History's Greatest Hoaxes
programme.desc: Hear how Orson Welles convinced millions of Americans that Earth really was being invaded by aliens.

programme.title: Britain's Forgotten Wars with Tony Robinson

programme.title: Cry Of The Wild
programme.desc: To hear Bill Mason tell about the making of this feature film (he is also the narrator) is to share with him his affection for his camera-quarry: the big northern timber wolves and pure-white Arctic wolves.

programme.title: Firewords Louky Bersianik Jovette Marchessault Nicole Brossa
programme.desc: Firewords offers an intimate glimpse of three respected, controversial Québec writers.Louky Bersianik, Jovette Marchessault and Nicole Brossard have contributed greatly to the creation of a distinctive women's literature.

programme.title: Julie Obrien
programme.desc: This film is loosely structured around Julie O'Brien, eleven’s school assignment to write an essay about the old times in Newfoundland, how they have changed, how they are still remembered.

programme.title: Ryan
programme.desc: Ryan is based on the life of Ryan Larkin, a Canadian animator who, 30 years ago, produced some of the most influential animated films of his time.

programme.title: Spirit Of The Kata
programme.desc: Five women, all of them black belts in karate, are examples of how this ancient martial art can transform lives. They demonstrate how it can generate a whole range of physical, psychological and spiritual benefits.

programme.title: The Lost Pharaoh The Search For Akhenaten
programme.desc: This documentary tells the fascinating story of an ancient pharaoh who was almost lost to history, and the archaeological sleuthing that went into piecing together information about him.

programme.title: Beautiful Lennard Island
programme.desc: Steven Holland, age ten, is the son of the lighthouse-keeper in charge of Lennard Island, a tiny place west of Vancouver Island. He takes us on a tour and dispels any ideas we might have that living in isolation is boring.

programme.title: Goddess Remembered
programme.desc: This poetic documentary is a salute to 35 000 years of "pre-history," to the values of ancestors only recently remembered, and to the goddess-worshipping religions of the ancient past.

programme.title: The Street
programme.desc: A poignant adaptation of Mordecai Richler's short story candidly depicts families' responses to aging members. Through watercolor and ink, the filmmaker captures raw family emotions, reflecting harsh realities.

programme.title: Strings
programme.desc: Strings: a haunting film of intimate strangers linked by shared spaces. Comfortable connections fracture when a problem arises. Created with glass painting and stop-motion, it's visually stunning.

programme.title: The Sweater
programme.desc: Roch Carrier narrates a childhood mishap in "The Hockey Sweater." In rural Quebec, boys idolize Maurice "Rocket" Richard. When the protagonist receives a Toronto Maple Leafs jersey instead of a Canadiens one, embarrassment ensues at the local rink.

programme.title: How They Saw Us Is It A Womans World
programme.desc: This film, made especially for television in 1956, embodies the conventional myth that women indirectly exercise power through their ability to manipulate men through sex and marriage.

programme.title: A Mother And Daughter On Abortion
programme.desc: The document of an intimate conversation between a mother and her adult daughter. They speak candidly about their personal experiences in trying to obtain an abortion, and how, in different decade, each got caught up in the system and its rules.

programme.title: Perfecting The Art Of Longing
programme.desc: Using footage from security cameras, video calls and home-video archives, this experimental short film leads us on a journey through memory, family and faith, exploring the nature of connection and distance.

programme.title: Sunrise Over Tiananmen Square
programme.desc: Shui-Bo Wang's animated documentary intertwines personal journey with history, exploring China's '60s-'80s upheavals. From symbol of hope to tragedy, it depicts Wang's roles from Red Guard to teacher, exploring idealism and intolerance.

programme.title: If You Love This Planet
programme.desc: This film records a lecture given to students by outspoken nuclear critic, Dr. Helen Caldicott, president of Physicians for Social Responsibility in the United States. Her message is clear: disarmament cannot be postponed.

programme.title: Chaque Enfant
programme.desc: This is the story of a baby who appears mysteriously on the doorstep of a busy executive, and who is subsequently bounced from household to household down the block. Nobody in the community is interested in caring for the baby without a name.

programme.title: Notmans World
programme.desc: William Notman was a man of rare talent. Photography was still in its infancy when he opened his first studio--in Montréal--in the late 1850s. He rapidly turned his art, and a budding technology, into a highly successful business.

programme.title: Mary Two-Axe Earley I Am Indian Again
programme.desc: This film shares the powerful story of Mary Two-Axe Earley, who fought for more than two decades to challenge sex discrimination against First Nations women embedded in Canada’s Indian Act and became a key figure in Canada’s women’s rights movement.

programme.title: The Secret Order
programme.desc: Phil Comeau shines a spotlight on the Ordre de Jacques-Cartier and paints a gripping portrait of the social and political struggles of Canadian francophone-minority communities.

programme.title: Canada Vignettes Log Drivers Waltz
programme.desc: A young girl who loves to dance and is ready to marry chooses a log driver over his more well-to-do, land-loving competition. Driving logs down the river has made him the best dancing partner to be found.

programme.title: The Man Who Stole Dreams
programme.desc: This enchanting and magical animation film, an ode to our dreams during the night, celebrates the creative imagination, uniqueness, and the human spirit. The plot involves a man who steals the dreams of villagers, the tries to sell them back to the them.

programme.title: Tu As Crie Let Me Go
programme.desc: In "Tu as crié LET ME GO," Anne Claire Poirier explores her daughter's tragic descent into drugs and prostitution, seeking understanding of the societal pressures influencing young people's risky behaviors in Montreal's streets.

programme.title: Best Time Of My Life Portraits Of Women In Mid-Life, The
programme.desc: An upbeat, positive film about a group of women dealing with mid-life and menopause. The women come from a wide range of backgrounds, careers and lifestyles, it effectively dispels popular myths and fears about life during and after menopause.

programme.title: Gurdeep Singh Bains
programme.desc: Gurdeep is a thirteen-year-old Canadian Sikh whose family runs a dairy farm near Chilliwack, British Columbia. They have retained their language and religion. Sometimes he feels a little different from the other children because he wears a turban.

programme.title: Le Grand Serpent Du Monde
programme.desc: A young forty-something, Tom Paradise refuses to grow up. Behind the wheel of his bus he drives endlessly through the city, tracing out the path of his life, dreaming of the landscape of the American West that forever impressed him

programme.title: Lieder, Land & Leute zu Gast im Defereggental
programme.desc: Dagmar Obernosterer präsentiert in dieser Folge der beliebten Fernsehsendung Lieder, Land und Leute das Defereggental in Osttirol. Wenn Landschaften Lieder schreiben könnten, dann würde die naturbelassene, herrliche Bergkulisse des Defereggentals wohl auch jeden musikalischen Wettbewerb gewinnen. In einem der unberührtesten Hochgebirgstälern der Alpen mit saftigen Almwiesen, Bergseen, seltenen Pflanzen und Tieren präsentieren die bekanntesten Interpreten der volkstümlichen Schlagermusik ihre Hits.

programme.title: Bei Hübner
programme.desc: Geboren wurde Ireen Sheer in England am 25. Februar 1949. Bevor sie sich ganz auf ihre Musik konzentrierte, machte sie zunächst eine Banklehre. In den 70er-Jahren hatte sie in Deutschland ihren großen Durchbruch und zählt bis heute zu den erfolgreichsten Schlagersängerinnen des Landes. Dieser Talk-Klassiker ist ein faszinierendes Zeitdokument einer außergewöhnlich erfolgreichen Künstlerin, die Ende 2022 ihr Karriereende bekanntgab.

programme.title: Herzgschichtn
programme.desc: Er ist in Bayern dahoam und in der Welt zu Hause, doch sein Herz wird immer für seine bayerische Heimat schlagen. Max Weidner, der Sänger aus der Oberpfalz, der bunte Tattoos, seine Herkunft und die Liebe zum Schlager miteinander vereint, ist zu Gast in Kirchberg bei Kitzbühel. Im Gespräch mit Anja Viktoria Autenrieth macht er deutlich, dass es ihm im Leben nicht darum geht, reich, schön oder berühmt zu sein. Vielmehr geht es darum, sich selbst treu zu bleiben und sich dabei auch nicht immer allzu ernst zu nehmen.

programme.desc: Das Meer verwandelt sich zusehends. Die azurblaue See von Durban unterscheidet sich grundlegend von der rauen Meeresküste des Kaps. Gemeinsam mit dem österreichischen Haiforscher Dietmar Posch startet Andreas auf eine Expedition in die warmen Gewässer vor der Küste

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Andreas lange Reise führt ihn schließlich und endlich in den Busch – ins „echte“ Afrika. Hier begibt er sich auf die Fährte der typischsten wilden Afrikaner – der Big Five. Und wo könnte er das besser als im Krüger Nationalpark, dem Wahrzeichen Südafrikas.

programme.title: Nigel Marvens wilde Philippinen
programme.desc: Palawan, die westlichste Insel des Archipels, ist als letzte Grenze bekannt. Nigel wird seine alten Regenwälder, unberührten Küsten, Korallenriffe und unglaublichen unterirdischen Schätze erkunden.

programme.title: Wilde Schönheiten: Ägypten
programme.desc: Ägypten bedeutet Pharaonen, Pyramiden und vor allem – Wüste. In der feindlichen Umgebung leben alle Arten von Tieren. Die alten Ägypter glaubten, dass diese Kreaturen die Natur, Mond, Tag und Nacht kontrollieren.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Inmitten von himmlisch schönen Bergeshöhen thront der Piz Beverin über dem Naturpark, dem er seinen Namen verleiht. Zu seinen Füßen erstreckt sich eine Landschaft voller wilder Natur. Tiefe Schluchten und glasklare Bergseen, artenreiche Trockenwiesen und seltene Moore, majestätische Steinböcke und zurückkehrende Wölfe.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Unendliche Wälder, eine herbe, unversehrte Natur und launisches Wetter prägen den Naturpark Waadtländer Jura. Wer einmal dort war, weiß um seinen besonderen Reiz: den der Abgeschiedenheit. Mit seinen Seen, Wäldern und von Trockenmauern geprägten Weiden steht das Naturjuwel für das ewige Zusammenspiel von Mensch und Natur. Das Grenzgebiet zu Frankreich bedeckt der riesige Risoud-Wald.

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika

programme.title: Der Whisky-Mythos von Islay
programme.desc: Die schottische Insel Islay ist Heimat von acht traditionellen Whisky-Brennereien, die unter Kennern einen ausgezeichneten Ruf genießen. Das Wasser, der Torf und das Jod des Meeres sind die besonderen Elemente des Whiskys, der die Insel berühmt gemacht hat. Doch nicht nur das: Die Herstellung des berühmten Getränks sorgt für Arbeitsplätze auf Islay, ist Stolz und zugleich Lebensgrundlage ihrer charismatischen Bewohner. Planet Weltweit hat die Insel besucht und erlebt, wie das schottische Nationalgetränk Leben und Arbeit der Menschen auf Islay bestimmt.

programme.title: Marokkos weißes Gold
programme.desc: Die Arganie, ein dornenbewehrter Baum, wächst nur im Südwesten Marokkos. Seine Früchte liefern das begehrte Arganöl, welches von den Frauen der Region seit Jahrhunderten in mühevoller Handarbeit produziert wird. Inzwischen kommen auch Europäer auf den Geschmack dieser einzigartigen Kostbarkeit. Und nicht nur das: Neben seinen kulinarischen Qualitäten lässt sich das Öl ebenso gut als Kosmetikprodukt und Heilmittel vermarkten. Planet Weltweit hat den Frauen Marokkos bei der aufwändigen Ölherstellung über die Schulter geschaut und beobachtet, wie sie sie versuchen, ihr traditionelles Kleinod für den internationalen Wettbewerb vorzubereiten.Sechs Uhr morgens in einem kleinen Dorf im Südwesten Marokkos. Die Männer sind bereits zur Arbeit aufgebrochen. Auch Arbia el Kasri verlässt das Haus, um ihrem Beruf nachzugehen. Vor fünf Jahren noch war es für eine Frau unvorstellbar außerhalb des Hauses Arbeit zu finden. In dieser Region Marokkos verlassen die Bäuerinnen eigentlich nie ihre Douar, ihre kleinen Dörfer. Doch nun sind es einige Hunderte, die sich wie Arbia täglich in kleinen Kooperativen einfinden, welche die Frauen selbst gegründet haben. Hier produzieren sie Arganöl - eine Kunst, die Marokkanerinnen bereits seit Jahrhunderten beherrschen. Das Öl ist überaus nährstoffre ...

programme.title: Der Weinpriester von Bali
programme.desc: Bali - Tropenparadies und Insel der Götter. Dem 42-jährigen Hindu Rai Budarsa gelang es als Erstem, Wein auf Bali zu kultivieren. Dreimal im Jahr kann auf der tropischen Insel geerntet werden. Für den Unternehmer ein Segen - doch für den gläubigen Hindu in Anbetracht der vielen religiösen Feste und Zeremonien eine Herausforderung. Ob Rai Budarsa der Balanceakt zwischen dem harten Alltag eines Unternehmers und seinen religiösen Verpflichtungen gelingt, davon erzählt diese Episode von Planet Weltweit.Bereits seit einer Stunde wartet die Prozession für die Leichenbestattung auf der Straße. Rai Budarsa streift eilig sein Poloshirt und die Bermudas ab, denn als höchster Vertreter einer Priesterkaste muss er jede Zeremonie in seiner Gemeinde leiten. Als sein Blackberry klingelt, schafft er es gerade noch den Knoten seines schwarzen Sarongs festzuziehen, bevor er den Anruf entgegennimmt. Es ist sein Kellermeister, der Australier Don Buchanan: Ihm fehlen Flaschen für die Abfüllung des Pino de Bali, dem Spitzenprodukt seines Unternehmens Hatten Wines. Der Container mit den Flaschen hängt irgendwo fest - ausgerechnet jetzt, wo während der religiösen Feiertage auf Bali die Restaurants und Hotels mit dem regionalen Wein beliefert werden müssen. Im Laufschritt verspricht Rai Budar ...

programme.title: Die Köchin von Bahia
programme.desc: Die afro-brasilianische Kultur ist nirgendwo so lebendig wie in Salvador de Bahia und in der Religion Candombl?. Die Köchin Elaine Cruz lebt und kocht nach den Regeln dieser Religion und zaubert einzigartige Spezialitäten, die Götter und Menschen gleichermaßen munden. Planet Weltweit hat Elaine beim Kochen für ein großes Fest einer Candombl?-Gemeinde über die Schulter geschaut.

programme.title: Brasilien
programme.desc: Die Einwohner der Amazonas-Insel Marajo nutzen außergewöhnliche Reittiere, um die sumpfigen Mangrovenwälder ihrer Heimat zu durchdringen: asiatische Wasserbüffel. Sie dienen als Nutz-, Haus- und Arbeitstiere, selbst die Polizei greift auf sie zurück: als einzige berittene Büffelstaffel der Welt. Planet Weltweit hat die ungewöhnliche Truppe bei der Arbeit mit den wuchtigen Reittieren begleitet.

programme.title: Im Land der schwarzen Witwen
programme.desc: Die Schwarze Witwe hat einen schlechten Ruf, kein Wunder, denn das Gift dieser Spinnenart ist 15-mal stärker als das der Klapperschlange. Doch kann diese Substanz, als Medizin eingesetzt, auch Leben retten. Um an das Gift zu gelangen, geht das Ehepaar Kristensen regelmäßig in der Wüste von Arizona auf Spinnenjagd. Wir begleiten die Fangaktionen und die Zucht der hochgiftigen Tiere.

programme.title: Tasmanien
programme.desc: Tasmanien ist ein einzigartiges Naturparadies: Wilde Strände, dichter Regenwald, zerklüftete Bergketten und alpine Moorlandschaften vereinen sich auf engstem Raum. Auf der Insel leben Wombats, Schnabeligel und Tasmanische Teufel. Die Rangerin Lalani Hyatt patrouilliert täglich durch das Arthur-Pieman-Schutzgebiet, bekämpft Waldbrände, stellt Umweltsünder oder rettet verwaiste Jungtiere.

programme.title: Indien Summer am Polarkreis
programme.desc: Der Herrgott, so ein Sprichwort in der Region, hat ihn nach der Schöpfung einfach vergessen: den Wald im Muddus Nationalpark in Schweden. Ein Urwald - die eine Hälfte voller Bäume, die andere voller Sümpfe und Seen, in dem die älteste Kiefer Schwedens steht. Wenn der Herbst die Bäume und Moose in goldgelbe und tiefrote Farbe taucht, spricht man auch hier im hohen Norden vom Indian Summer.

programme.title: Das Perlenimperium von Palawan
programme.desc: Sie schimmert warm und golden, die Oberfläche ist makellos: So sieht die perfekte Perle der goldlippigen Auster Pinctada Maxima aus. Ihr Wert - mehrere Tausend Euro. In freier Natur findet nur sich in einer von 20.000 Austern eine solche Kostbarkeit. Das Unternehmen Jewelmer hat deshalb vor Jahren angefangen, in den Gewässern des philippinischen Archipels Palawan, diese Austern zu züchten. Bis heute beträgt ihre Ausbeute mehrere Millionen Euro pro Jahr. Diesen Erfolg hat das Unternehmen einer akribischen Forschung und einer rigiden Personalpolitik zu verdanken. Planet hat den Archipel besucht und beobachtet, wie lange es dauert, der Natur diese seltenen Kostbarkeiten abzuringen.

programme.title: Gerry Mulligan, Dave Glenn, Harold Danko & Ed Neumeister
programme.sub-title: Gerry Mulligan Big Band - The North Sea Jazz
programme.desc: The North Sea Jazz Festival is the largest indoor music festival in the world, known globally as the event where the past, present and future of jazz are featured within three days. Next to a firm base of jazz as the festival's staple music genre, many others, such as blues, soul, funk, or hip hop, pass by. In 1982, American saxophonist Gerry Mulligan gave an unforgettable performance at the North Sea Jazz Festival in The Hague. Mulligan was one of the leading arrangers of the cool jazz era, who worked with Miles Davis, Stan Kenton and Claude Thornhill in the 1950s and 1960s. Mulligan's early pianoless 1950s quartet with trumpeter Chet Baker is still regarded as one of the finest groups in cool jazz. Born in New York in 1927, Mulligan spent his life composing, arranging and playing jazz until his death on January 20, 1996.

programme.title: Ted Curson

programme.title: Avishai Cohen
programme.desc: Double bassist Avishai Cohen's trio with Noam David (drums) and Omri Mor (pianist) joined forces with the international Symphony Orchestra ‘INSO-Lviv', conducted by Christian Schumann. On June 24, 2017 they brought Avishai Cohen's signature blend of influences from Eastern Europe, American jazz and the Middle East to the Alfa Jazz Festival in Lviv, Ukraine. Cohen, who also supplies vocalizations in the Judeo-Spanish dialect Ladino, came to prominence internationally in the 1990s when jazz great Chick Corea offered him a place in his trio and a recording deal. Thirty years later, Cohen has become a house-hold name himself, leaving his Ukrainian audience enthralled and connected through the universal language of music.

programme.title: Herbie Hancock & The Headhunter
programme.desc: American keyboard player and bandleader Herbie Hancock (1940) achieved success as an incisive, harmonically provocative jazz pianist in the 1960s, then went on to gain wide popularity as a leader of electric jazz-rock groups. One of these, Hancock's band The Headhunters, ushered in a new era of jazz that appealed to a far wider audience, making jazz listeners out of rhythm and blues fans, and vice versa. In 1974, The Headhunters appeared on German television, playing Palm Grease, Sly, Butterfly, Spank-A-Lee, and Chameleon. Hancock (keys) is joined by Bennie Maupin (saxophones), Paul Jackson (electric bass), Mike Clark (drums) and Bill Summer (percussion).

On June 24, 2017 they brought Avishai Cohen's signature blend of influences from Eastern Europe, American jazz and the Middle East to the Alfa Jazz Festival in Lviv, Ukraine. Cohen, who also supplies vocalizations in the Judeo-Spanish dialect Ladino, came to prominence internationally in the 1990s when jazz great Chick Corea offered him a place in his trio and a recording deal. Thirty years later, Cohen has become a house-hold name himself, leaving his Ukrainian audience enthralled and connected through the universal language of music.

programme.title: Manu Dibango, Daniel Rallo, Jerry Malekani & Frederic Gaillardet
programme.sub-title: Soul Makossa: Manu Dibango in Stuttgart
programme.desc: Manu Dibango, one of Africa's biggest musical stars and top saxophonists, is an indispensable artist. He was one of the first African musicians to score a worldwide hit with his 1972 release “Soul Makossa”, paving the way for many other artists. The very concept of world music owes much to him. A superb stage performer with great communicative humour, Dibango is above all one of the founding fathers of a modern African musical style that is open to jazz, R&B, salsa, gospel, funk, and reggae. This concert showcases all these genres, and features an excellent line-up of musicians from the four corners of the planet.

programme.title: Steve Gadd
programme.desc: Many of pianist Chick Corea's compositions have become jazz standards. As a member of Miles Davis' band in the late 1960s, he participated in the birth of the electric jazz fusion movement. In the 1970s, Corea founded the legendary jazz fusion group Return to Forever. Along with Herbie Hancock, McCoy Tyner and Keith Jarrett, Corea is one of the biggest modern jazz pianists. He continued musical collaborations with a diverse range of artists, exploring various musical styles. This broadcast features three performances that illustrate Chick Corea's many talents.

programme.title: Gilberto Gil
programme.desc: Brazilian artist Gilberto Gil returns to Jazz à Vienne in France with a new round of singing that is inspired by his latest album ‘Fé na Festa': a mixture of celebration, tradition and even some rock now and then. Gilberto Gil, worldwide known for as musician and the Brazilian minister of Culture, was one of the pioneers of the cultural movement ‘tropicalismo'. This movement, with a strong character of social protest, combines elements of traditional Brazilian culture with modern art forms. Gilberto Gil's new sound clearly has its roots in Brazilian culture, yet it is always inspired by jazz.

programme.title: Ballet of the Mariinsky Theatre
programme.desc: The Mariinsky Ballet performs 'Anna Karenina', a sweeping two-act ballet choreographed by Alexei Ratmansky. The ballet is based on Lev Tolstoy's 1877 novel that tells the tragic story of the married socialite Anna Karenina and her affair with cavalry officer Count Vronsky. The ballet opens where the novel ends: tormented by despair and loneliness, Anna throws herself under a train, whereupon Count Vronsky discovers his lover's lifeless body. Ratmansky's choreography is set to Rodion Shchedrin's music, which is performed by the Mariinsky Orchestra under the baton of Valery Gergiev. Among the dancers are Ulyana Lopatkina, Victor Baranov, Andrei Yermakov, and Svetlana Ivanova. This performance was recorded at the Mariinsky Theatre in St. Petersburg, Russia, in March 2014.

programme.title: Nikolay Lugansky & Vadim Rudenko
programme.sub-title: Piano Duets - Mozart, Ravel, Rachmaninoff a. o.
programme.desc: In this splendid concert, exceptional Russian pianists Nikolay Lugansky and Vadim Rudenko join forces in a program for two pianos comprising works of Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, Maurice Ravel, Anton Arensky, Sergei Rachmaninoff, and Nikolai Kapustin. Both pianists, laureates of the prestigious International Tchaikovsky Competition in 1994, have received international recognition. They perform regularly in a duo. On the program: Mozart's Sonata for two pianos in D major, K. 448/375 A Ravel's La Valse (arr. for two pianos) Arensky's Suite No. 1 for two pianos, Op. 15 and Rachmaninoff's Suite No. 1 (Fantasy) for two pianos, Op. 5. As an encore, the duo performs ‘Romance' from Rachmaninoff's Suite No. 2 for two pianos, Op. 17, followed by ‘Overture' from Nikolai Kapustin's Sinfonietta, Op. 49. This performance was recorded at the Tchaikovsky Concert Hall in Moscow, Russia, on November 25, 2021.

programme.title: David Grimal & Les Dissonances
programme.sub-title: Beethoven - Symphony No. 5 in C minor, Op. 67
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances perform Ludwig van Beethoven's Symphony No. 5 in C minor, Op. 67. Beethoven composed Symphony No. 5 between 1804 and 1808, completing the work at nearly the same time as his Symphony No. 6, ‘Pastorale'. Both symphonies premiered as part of an all-Beethoven program at the same concert on December 22, 1808. Symphony No. 5 has become one of the best-known compositions in classical music. It opens with the famous four-note motif, often interpreted as the musical manifestation of 'fate knocking at the door'. This rhythmic figure returns in various guises in the other three movements of the symphony. The second movement consists of a set of lyrical variations on two themes. The third movement begins gently, but leads to a blasting horn section presenting a theme that features the rhythmic pattern of the four-note motif. The movement leads uninterrupted to the fourth movement that features a triumphant finale ending in C major. This performance was recorded at Philharmonie de Paris, France, in 2015.

programme.title: David Grimal & Les Dissonances
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances play Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart's Violin Concerto No. 4 in D major, K. 218. Leading violinist Grimal features as the soloist. With the exception of the first violin concerto, Mozart composed his other four violin concertos in 1775 at a time when he was concertmaster at the Salzburg court. Among his five concertos, Violin Concerto No. 4 is one of the best-known. This performance was recorded at Cité de la Musique, France, in 2014.

programme.title: Adrien Perruchon, Symfonieorkest Vlaanderen & Josef Špaček
programme.sub-title: Works by Ravel, Lalo, Ginastera a. o.
programme.desc: French conductor Adrien Perruchon and the Flanders Symphony Orchestra take us on a musical journey to Argentine, Spain, and Mexico, in this March 1, 2017 concert performance at Concertgebouw Brugge in Belgium. The program opens with Édouard Lalo's Spanish Symphony for violin and orchestra, Op. 21, featuring Czech violinist Josef Špaček as the soloist. This is followed by Mathias Coppens' Music for Orchestra, Op. 12. The program continues with Alberto Ginastera's Dances from Estancia, Op. 8a, and Aaron Copland's El Salón México. Also on the program is Maurice Ravel's famous Boléro. The program comes to a close with Arturo Márquez's Danzón No. 2.

programme.desc: Dagmar Obernosterer präsentiert in dieser Folge der beliebten Fernsehsendung Lieder, Land und Leute das Defereggental in Osttirol. Wenn Landschaften Lieder schreiben könnten, dann würde die naturbelassene, herrliche Bergkulisse des Defereggentals wohl auch jeden musikalischen Wettbewerb gewinnen. In einem der unberührtesten Hochgebirgstälern der Alpen mit saftigen Almwiesen, Bergseen, seltenen Pflanzen und Tieren präsentieren die bekanntesten Interpreten der volkstümlichen Schlagermusik ihre Hits.

programme.title: Bei Hübner
programme.desc: Geboren wurde Ireen Sheer in England am 25. Februar 1949. Bevor sie sich ganz auf ihre Musik konzentrierte, machte sie zunächst eine Banklehre. In den 70er-Jahren hatte sie in Deutschland ihren großen Durchbruch und zählt bis heute zu den erfolgreichsten Schlagersängerinnen des Landes. Dieser Talk-Klassiker ist ein faszinierendes Zeitdokument einer außergewöhnlich erfolgreichen Künstlerin, die Ende 2022 ihr Karriereende bekanntgab.

programme.title: Herzgschichtn
programme.desc: Er ist in Bayern dahoam und in der Welt zu Hause, doch sein Herz wird immer für seine bayerische Heimat schlagen. Max Weidner, der Sänger aus der Oberpfalz, der bunte Tattoos, seine Herkunft und die Liebe zum Schlager miteinander vereint, ist zu Gast in Kirchberg bei Kitzbühel. Im Gespräch mit Anja Viktoria Autenrieth macht er deutlich, dass es ihm im Leben nicht darum geht, reich, schön oder berühmt zu sein. Vielmehr geht es darum, sich selbst treu zu bleiben und sich dabei auch nicht immer allzu ernst zu nehmen.

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Andreas lange Reise führt ihn schließlich und endlich in den Busch – ins „echte“ Afrika. Hier begibt er sich auf die Fährte der typischsten wilden Afrikaner – der Big Five. Und wo könnte er das besser als im Krüger Nationalpark, dem Wahrzeichen Südafrikas.

programme.title: Nigel Marvens wilde Philippinen
programme.desc: Palawan, die westlichste Insel des Archipels, ist als letzte Grenze bekannt. Nigel wird seine alten Regenwälder, unberührten Küsten, Korallenriffe und unglaublichen unterirdischen Schätze erkunden.

programme.title: Wilde Schönheiten: Ägypten
programme.desc: Ägypten bedeutet Pharaonen, Pyramiden und vor allem – Wüste. In der feindlichen Umgebung leben alle Arten von Tieren. Die alten Ägypter glaubten, dass diese Kreaturen die Natur, Mond, Tag und Nacht kontrollieren.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Inmitten von himmlisch schönen Bergeshöhen thront der Piz Beverin über dem Naturpark, dem er seinen Namen verleiht. Zu seinen Füßen erstreckt sich eine Landschaft voller wilder Natur. Tiefe Schluchten und glasklare Bergseen, artenreiche Trockenwiesen und seltene Moore, majestätische Steinböcke und zurückkehrende Wölfe.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Unendliche Wälder, eine herbe, unversehrte Natur und launisches Wetter prägen den Naturpark Waadtländer Jura. Wer einmal dort war, weiß um seinen besonderen Reiz: den der Abgeschiedenheit. Mit seinen Seen, Wäldern und von Trockenmauern geprägten Weiden steht das Naturjuwel für das ewige Zusammenspiel von Mensch und Natur. Das Grenzgebiet zu Frankreich bedeckt der riesige Risoud-Wald.

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Das Meer verwandelt sich zusehends. Die azurblaue See von Durban unterscheidet sich grundlegend von der rauen Meeresküste des Kaps. Gemeinsam mit dem österreichischen Haiforscher Dietmar Posch startet Andreas auf eine Expedition in die warmen Gewässer vor der Küste

programme.title: Mitten im Südafrika
programme.desc: Andreas lange Reise führt ihn schließlich und endlich in den Busch – ins „echte“ Afrika. Hier begibt er sich auf die Fährte der typischsten wilden Afrikaner – der Big Five. Und wo könnte er das besser als im Krüger Nationalpark, dem Wahrzeichen Südafrikas.

programme.title: Kinderstube Wildnis Bei den Löwen
programme.desc: Eine alleinerziehende Löwin hat es nicht leicht in Afrikas Savannen. Löwen-Mama Nyota hat keine Beschützer und muss für sich und ihren fünf Monate alten Sohn Moja ganz alleine sorgen. Vor der Regenzeit sind Beutetiere spärlich und die besten Reviere von großen Löwenrudeln besetzt. Auf sich alleine gestellt, muss Nyota zwischen ihrem knurrenden Magen und dem Schutz des Kleinen abwägen. Es gelingt ihr kaum, sich einmal satt zu essen. Entweder die Jagdversuche bleiben erfolglos oder Hyänen machen ihr das mühsam erlegte Wild nach wenigen Bissen streitig. Alleine hat sie den Aasfressern kaum etwas entgegen zu setzen. Um Moja nicht in Gefahr zu bringen, verzichtet sie jedoch auf einen Kampf und überlässt ihren Fang der gierigen Meute. Berührende Szenen zeigen, wie das Duo trotz der immer weiter schwindenden Kräfte auch in den härtesten Wochen zusammenhält. Die Rettung der kleinen Familie naht in Form der heraufziehenden Gnu-Herden.

programme.title: Der Whisky-Mythos von Islay
programme.desc: Die schottische Insel Islay ist Heimat von acht traditionellen Whisky-Brennereien, die unter Kennern einen ausgezeichneten Ruf genießen. Das Wasser, der Torf und das Jod des Meeres sind die besonderen Elemente des Whiskys, der die Insel berühmt gemacht hat. Doch nicht nur das: Die Herstellung des berühmten Getränks sorgt für Arbeitsplätze auf Islay, ist Stolz und zugleich Lebensgrundlage ihrer charismatischen Bewohner. Planet Weltweit hat die Insel besucht und erlebt, wie das schottische Nationalgetränk Leben und Arbeit der Menschen auf Islay bestimmt.

programme.title: Marokkos weißes Gold
programme.desc: Die Arganie, ein dornenbewehrter Baum, wächst nur im Südwesten Marokkos. Seine Früchte liefern das begehrte Arganöl, welches von den Frauen der Region seit Jahrhunderten in mühevoller Handarbeit produziert wird. Inzwischen kommen auch Europäer auf den Geschmack dieser einzigartigen Kostbarkeit. Und nicht nur das: Neben seinen kulinarischen Qualitäten lässt sich das Öl ebenso gut als Kosmetikprodukt und Heilmittel vermarkten. Planet Weltweit hat den Frauen Marokkos bei der aufwändigen Ölherstellung über die Schulter geschaut und beobachtet, wie sie sie versuchen, ihr traditionelles Kleinod für den internationalen Wettbewerb vorzubereiten.Sechs Uhr morgens in einem kleinen Dorf im Südwesten Marokkos. Die Männer sind bereits zur Arbeit aufgebrochen. Auch Arbia el Kasri verlässt das Haus, um ihrem Beruf nachzugehen. Vor fünf Jahren noch war es für eine Frau unvorstellbar außerhalb des Hauses Arbeit zu finden. In dieser Region Marokkos verlassen die Bäuerinnen eigentlich nie ihre Douar, ihre kleinen Dörfer. Doch nun sind es einige Hunderte, die sich wie Arbia täglich in kleinen Kooperativen einfinden, welche die Frauen selbst gegründet haben. Hier produzieren sie Arganöl - eine Kunst, die Marokkanerinnen bereits seit Jahrhunderten beherrschen. Das Öl ist überaus nährstoffre ...

programme.title: Der Weinpriester von Bali
programme.desc: Bali - Tropenparadies und Insel der Götter. Dem 42-jährigen Hindu Rai Budarsa gelang es als Erstem, Wein auf Bali zu kultivieren. Dreimal im Jahr kann auf der tropischen Insel geerntet werden. Für den Unternehmer ein Segen - doch für den gläubigen Hindu in Anbetracht der vielen religiösen Feste und Zeremonien eine Herausforderung. Ob Rai Budarsa der Balanceakt zwischen dem harten Alltag eines Unternehmers und seinen religiösen Verpflichtungen gelingt, davon erzählt diese Episode von Planet Weltweit.Bereits seit einer Stunde wartet die Prozession für die Leichenbestattung auf der Straße. Rai Budarsa streift eilig sein Poloshirt und die Bermudas ab, denn als höchster Vertreter einer Priesterkaste muss er jede Zeremonie in seiner Gemeinde leiten. Als sein Blackberry klingelt, schafft er es gerade noch den Knoten seines schwarzen Sarongs festzuziehen, bevor er den Anruf entgegennimmt. Es ist sein Kellermeister, der Australier Don Buchanan: Ihm fehlen Flaschen für die Abfüllung des Pino de Bali, dem Spitzenprodukt seines Unternehmens Hatten Wines. Der Container mit den Flaschen hängt irgendwo fest - ausgerechnet jetzt, wo während der religiösen Feiertage auf Bali die Restaurants und Hotels mit dem regionalen Wein beliefert werden müssen. Im Laufschritt verspricht Rai Budar ...

programme.title: Die Köchin von Bahia
programme.desc: Die afro-brasilianische Kultur ist nirgendwo so lebendig wie in Salvador de Bahia und in der Religion Candombl?. Die Köchin Elaine Cruz lebt und kocht nach den Regeln dieser Religion und zaubert einzigartige Spezialitäten, die Götter und Menschen gleichermaßen munden. Planet Weltweit hat Elaine beim Kochen für ein großes Fest einer Candombl?-Gemeinde über die Schulter geschaut.

programme.title: Brasilien
programme.desc: Die Einwohner der Amazonas-Insel Marajo nutzen außergewöhnliche Reittiere, um die sumpfigen Mangrovenwälder ihrer Heimat zu durchdringen: asiatische Wasserbüffel. Sie dienen als Nutz-, Haus- und Arbeitstiere, selbst die Polizei greift auf sie zurück: als einzige berittene Büffelstaffel der Welt. Planet Weltweit hat die ungewöhnliche Truppe bei der Arbeit mit den wuchtigen Reittieren begleitet.

programme.title: Im Land der schwarzen Witwen
programme.desc: Die Schwarze Witwe hat einen schlechten Ruf, kein Wunder, denn das Gift dieser Spinnenart ist 15-mal stärker als das der Klapperschlange. Doch kann diese Substanz, als Medizin eingesetzt, auch Leben retten. Um an das Gift zu gelangen, geht das Ehepaar Kristensen regelmäßig in der Wüste von Arizona auf Spinnenjagd. Wir begleiten die Fangaktionen und die Zucht der hochgiftigen Tiere.

programme.title: Tasmanien
programme.desc: Tasmanien ist ein einzigartiges Naturparadies: Wilde Strände, dichter Regenwald, zerklüftete Bergketten und alpine Moorlandschaften vereinen sich auf engstem Raum. Auf der Insel leben Wombats, Schnabeligel und Tasmanische Teufel. Die Rangerin Lalani Hyatt patrouilliert täglich durch das Arthur-Pieman-Schutzgebiet, bekämpft Waldbrände, stellt Umweltsünder oder rettet verwaiste Jungtiere.

programme.title: Indien Summer am Polarkreis
programme.desc: Der Herrgott, so ein Sprichwort in der Region, hat ihn nach der Schöpfung einfach vergessen: den Wald im Muddus Nationalpark in Schweden. Ein Urwald - die eine Hälfte voller Bäume, die andere voller Sümpfe und Seen, in dem die älteste Kiefer Schwedens steht. Wenn der Herbst die Bäume und Moose in goldgelbe und tiefrote Farbe taucht, spricht man auch hier im hohen Norden vom Indian Summer.

programme.title: Das Perlenimperium von Palawan
programme.desc: Sie schimmert warm und golden, die Oberfläche ist makellos: So sieht die perfekte Perle der goldlippigen Auster Pinctada Maxima aus. Ihr Wert - mehrere Tausend Euro. In freier Natur findet nur sich in einer von 20.000 Austern eine solche Kostbarkeit. Das Unternehmen Jewelmer hat deshalb vor Jahren angefangen, in den Gewässern des philippinischen Archipels Palawan, diese Austern zu züchten. Bis heute beträgt ihre Ausbeute mehrere Millionen Euro pro Jahr. Diesen Erfolg hat das Unternehmen einer akribischen Forschung und einer rigiden Personalpolitik zu verdanken. Planet hat den Archipel besucht und beobachtet, wie lange es dauert, der Natur diese seltenen Kostbarkeiten abzuringen.

programme.desc: Ninguna otra dinastía está más estrechamente ligada al destino de Alemania que la de los Hohenzollern. De esta familia salieron príncipes, reyes y emperadores. Hace cien años, en noviembre de 1918, su reinado llegó a su fin. ¿Cómo afrontan los descendientes el legado de sus antepasados? ¿Qué caminos han tomado? La propia familia proporciona las respuestas. En la película, Georg Friedrich, Príncipe de Prusia, y Karl Friedrich, Príncipe de Hohenzollern, ofrecen en exclusiva una visión personal de la familia.

programme.title: La Vida de la Reina

programme.title: Diana: La Noche en que Murió
programme.desc: Nunca se han planteado muchas preguntas sencillas sobre la fatídica noche del 31 de agosto. Al final no sólo murió la princesa Diana, sino también Dodi Al Fayed y el conductor Henri Paul. En primer lugar, la policía culpó a los paparazzi de causar el accidente. Habían estado "zumbando alrededor del coche como moscas". 48 horas después, culparon al conductor del Mercedes, Henri Paul. Se dice que triplicaba la tasa de alcoholemia permitida. Este convincente programa trata de responder a las muchas preguntas que la investigación ha pasado por alto y de desvelar lo que ocurrió realmente la noche en que murió Diana.

programme.title: 술이 익는 소리. 막걸리 빚기
programme.desc: 막걸리의 어원은 체나 거름망으로 막 걸렀거나, 방금 바로 걸렀다는 뜻에서 유래하였습니다. 전통적인 방법으로 막걸리를 빚는 '막걸리 빚기'는 생활 문화이자 국가무형유산인데요. 전통의 기법을 고수하고 있는 전천 덕산 양조장에서 막걸리가 익어가는 소리와 전 과정을 영상미 있게 담아냈습니다. (이방희 / 2003년 등록문화재 진천 덕산 양조장 대표)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 혼이 담긴 바늘과 색실. 자수장
programme.desc: 우리 생활 도구에 멋을 놓았던 전통자수. 이를 복원한 김시인 자수장의 '무아지경'의 작업의 순간을 ASMR로 담았습니다. 한땀 한땀 바늘로 이루는 끈기의 미학이라 할 수 있는 전통자수의 아름다움에 빠져봅시다. (김시인 / 경북무형문화재 자수장 보유자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 바다가 만든 한 그릇. 통영 너물비빔밥
programme.desc: 다양한 지역에 전통 비빔밥이 있지만 통영의 비빔밥은 생김새부터 남다릅니다. 제사 음식에서 비롯했기 때문인지 두부탕국을 곁들이는데요. 또한 해조류가 매우 풍부해 생미역과 톳나물을 비빔밥의 주재료로 이용합니다. 이외에도 계절에 따라 오이, 박, 미나리, 쑥갓 등 10가지 이상의 나물을 넣어 만든 통영의 풍성한 향토음식을 ASMR로 만나보세요. (이상희 / 전통음식문화연구가)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 소리의 맥을 잇다, 대금장
programme.desc: 대금은 대나무에 구멍을 뚫어 소리를 내는 관악기로, 옛 사대부들의 풍류를 상징하는 한국의 대표적인 전통악기 중 하나입니다. 대금 제작자들은 스스로 악기를 연주할 수 있는 대금 연주자이기도 한데요. 실제 연주자로서도 활발하게 활동하며 대금장으로서 전통의 맥을 잇고 있는 장인의 작업과정을 따라가 보시죠.(이정대 / 인천광역시 무형문화재 대금장 보유자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 봄을 맞이하다. 궁중병과 봄차림상
programme.desc: 봄과 가장 잘 어울리는 완벽한 간식, 궁중병과를 만드는 소리를 담아봤습니다. 봄향기 가득한 화사한 진달래로 만드는 진달래 화전, 다양한 재료로 예쁘게 색을 낸 삼색쌀강정, 그리고 달콤하고 톡 쏘는 오미자 화채를 만드는 모습을 함께 감상해보시죠. (박영미 / 국가무형문화재 조선왕조궁중음식 이수자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 천년을 견디는 한지의 비밀. 닥나무 껍질 벗기기
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널전통 한지는 천 년을 견디며 변하지 않는 뛰어난 가치를 지니고 있습니다. 99번의 손길을 거쳐 100번째 탄생하는 땀과 정신의 결정체인 전통 한지의 제작 과정 중 주원료가 되는 닥나무의 껍질을 벗기는 과정을 함께 감상해보시죠. (김춘호 / 경북무형문화재 문경 한지장 전승교육사)

programme.title: 경복궁, 비에 젖다. 우중궁궐
programme.desc: 비 오는 날의 경복궁으로 초대합니다. 궁궐의 잿빛 박석 위로 떨어지는 빗물들은 박석 이음매를 따라 유유히 하수구로 흘러들고, 경회루가 못에 비쳐 아른거리는 모습이 있는 궁궐의 풍경은 내리는 비를 맞으며 궁 안을 걷고 싶어지게 하죠. 차분한 빗소리가 어우러진 궁궐의 아름다움을 함께 느껴보세요. ※ 경복궁 (사적 제117호)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 병풍을 만들다, 배첩장
programme.desc: 배첩은 글씨나 그림의 보존성과 아름다움을 높이기 위한 전통 서화 처리기법을 말합니다. 액자를 만들거나 병풍, 족자, 책을 엮는 등의 작업을 주로 하는데, 장인의 솜씨가 그 퀄리티를 좌우하죠. 배첩장이 10폭 병풍을 만드는 과정을 함께 감상해보시죠. (홍종진 / 충북무형문화재 배첩장 보유자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 사방탁자를 만들다. 소목장
programme.desc: 소목장은 건물의 창호, 목기, 목가구를 제작하는 목수를 말합니다. 이들은 전통 목공예기법으로 무늬가 있는 나무를 사용하여 자연스러운 미를 살려냅니다. 검소한 조선시대 문방생활을 운치있게 만들어주던 사방탁자를 만드는 과정을 감상해 보세요. (박명배 / 국가무형문화재 소목장 보유자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 조선 도예의 맥을 잇다. 사기장
programme.desc: 백산 가문은 조선 영조시대 이래 300여년이 넘는 세월 동안 전통 도자기의 명맥을 이어오고 있습니다. 7대 김정옥 사기장은 아들이자 전수조교 김경식 그리고 손자이자 전수생인 김지훈과 함께 9대에 걸쳐 조선왕실 도예의 계보를 잇고 있는데요. 흙, 불, 그리고 사람이 빚어낸 그릇이 섭씨 1300도 장작 가마 속에서 견딘 후 일상으로 다가오는 과정을 감상해보세요. (김정옥 / 국가무형문화재 사기장 보유자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 인고의 시간을 이겨내다. 털 고르기
programme.desc: 필장은 문방사우(文房四友)의 하나인 붓을 만드는 장인입니다. 전통 붓 제작 과정에서 좋은 붓을 만들기 위해서는 털을 고르는 '정모 작업'이 필수적인데요. 수천 번의 손길을 거쳐야 완성되는 전통 붓의 정성을 함께 감상해보시죠. (유필무 / 충북무형문화재 필장 보유자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 씨줄날줄 엮어낸 조상의 멋. 왕골돗자리
programme.desc: 왕골은 습지에 사는 한해살이풀로 줄기의 껍질이 매우 질겨 다양한 생활공예품으로 사용되어 왔습니다. 특히 함평 왕골돗자리는 촉감이 상쾌하고 부드러우며, 왕골자체에 염분성분이 함유되어 땀 흡수력이 빨라 여름에는 시원하고 겨울에는 따뜻합니다. 온 마을 사람들이 한땀한땀 정성스럽게 만드는 신기한 돗자리 제작과정을 함께 감상해보시죠. (전라남도 함평군 외세마을)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: [신비롭고 아름다운 비경] 청송 주산지 EP.3
programme.desc: 주산지는 조선 경종(1720년) 10월에 준공하였습니다. 주산지의 맑은 물은 주산현 꼭대기 별바위에서 계곡을 따라 흘러 주산지에 머무르고 주왕산 영봉에서 뻗친 울창한 수림으로 둘러싸여 있으며, 물위에 떠있는 듯한 왕버들과 어우러져 별천지에 온 것 같이 한적하면서도 아늑한 분위기를 자아냅니다. ※ 청송 주산지 일원 (명승 제 105호) / 청송세계지질공원 (2017년 유네스코 세계지질공원)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: [오늘도 평화로운 갯벌] 바람에 흔들리는 갈대숲, 순천만
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널순천만은 남해안 중서부에 위치한 만으로, 갯벌에 펼쳐지는 갈대밭과 칠면초 군락 등이 어우러져 아름다운 해안 생태경관을 보입니다. 넓은 갯벌에는 다양한 갯벌 생물들이 살고, 천연기념물인 흑두루미를 비롯한 국제 희귀 조류가 찾는 순천만의 풍경을 감상해 보세요! ※ 전라남도 순천시 순천만 (명승 제41호) / 한국의 갯벌 (2021년 유네스코 세계자연유산)

programme.title: Gerry Mulligan, Dave Glenn, Harold Danko & Ed Neumeister
programme.sub-title: Gerry Mulligan Big Band - The North Sea Jazz
programme.desc: The North Sea Jazz Festival is the largest indoor music festival in the world, known globally as the event where the past, present and future of jazz are featured within three days. Next to a firm base of jazz as the festival's staple music genre, many others, such as blues, soul, funk, or hip hop, pass by. In 1982, American saxophonist Gerry Mulligan gave an unforgettable performance at the North Sea Jazz Festival in The Hague. Mulligan was one of the leading arrangers of the cool jazz era, who worked with Miles Davis, Stan Kenton and Claude Thornhill in the 1950s and 1960s. Mulligan's early pianoless 1950s quartet with trumpeter Chet Baker is still regarded as one of the finest groups in cool jazz. Born in New York in 1927, Mulligan spent his life composing, arranging and playing jazz until his death on January 20, 1996.

programme.title: Avishai Cohen
programme.desc: Double bassist Avishai Cohen's trio with Noam David (drums) and Omri Mor (pianist) joined forces with the international Symphony Orchestra ‘INSO-Lviv', conducted by Christian Schumann. On June 24, 2017 they brought Avishai Cohen's signature blend of influences from Eastern Europe, American jazz and the Middle East to the Alfa Jazz Festival in Lviv, Ukraine. Cohen, who also supplies vocalizations in the Judeo-Spanish dialect Ladino, came to prominence internationally in the 1990s when jazz great Chick Corea offered him a place in his trio and a recording deal. Thirty years later, Cohen has become a house-hold name himself, leaving his Ukrainian audience enthralled and connected through the universal language of music.

programme.title: Herbie Hancock & The Headhunter
programme.desc: American keyboard player and bandleader Herbie Hancock (1940) achieved success as an incisive, harmonically provocative jazz pianist in the 1960s, then went on to gain wide popularity as a leader of electric jazz-rock groups. One of these, Hancock's band The Headhunters, ushered in a new era of jazz that appealed to a far wider audience, making jazz listeners out of rhythm and blues fans, and vice versa. In 1974, The Headhunters appeared on German television, playing Palm Grease, Sly, Butterfly, Spank-A-Lee, and Chameleon. Hancock (keys) is joined by Bennie Maupin (saxophones), Paul Jackson (electric bass), Mike Clark (drums) and Bill Summer (percussion).

programme.title: Manu Dibango, Daniel Rallo, Jerry Malekani & Frederic Gaillardet
programme.sub-title: Soul Makossa: Manu Dibango in Stuttgart
programme.desc: Manu Dibango, one of Africa's biggest musical stars and top saxophonists, is an indispensable artist. He was one of the first African musicians to score a worldwide hit with his 1972 release “Soul Makossa”, paving the way for many other artists. The very concept of world music owes much to him. A superb stage performer with great communicative humour, Dibango is above all one of the founding fathers of a modern African musical style that is open to jazz, R&B, salsa, gospel, funk, and reggae. This concert showcases all these genres, and features an excellent line-up of musicians from the four corners of the planet.

programme.title: Steve Gadd
programme.desc: Many of pianist Chick Corea's compositions have become jazz standards. As a member of Miles Davis' band in the late 1960s, he participated in the birth of the electric jazz fusion movement. In the 1970s, Corea founded the legendary jazz fusion group Return to Forever. Along with Herbie Hancock, McCoy Tyner and Keith Jarrett, Corea is one of the biggest modern jazz pianists. He continued musical collaborations with a diverse range of artists, exploring various musical styles. This broadcast features three performances that illustrate Chick Corea's many talents.

programme.title: Gilberto Gil
programme.desc: Brazilian artist Gilberto Gil returns to Jazz à Vienne in France with a new round of singing that is inspired by his latest album ‘Fé na Festa': a mixture of celebration, tradition and even some rock now and then. Gilberto Gil, worldwide known for as musician and the Brazilian minister of Culture, was one of the pioneers of the cultural movement ‘tropicalismo'. This movement, with a strong character of social protest, combines elements of traditional Brazilian culture with modern art forms. Gilberto Gil's new sound clearly has its roots in Brazilian culture, yet it is always inspired by jazz.

programme.title: Ballet of the Mariinsky Theatre
programme.desc: The Mariinsky Ballet performs 'Anna Karenina', a sweeping two-act ballet choreographed by Alexei Ratmansky. The ballet is based on Lev Tolstoy's 1877 novel that tells the tragic story of the married socialite Anna Karenina and her affair with cavalry officer Count Vronsky. The ballet opens where the novel ends: tormented by despair and loneliness, Anna throws herself under a train, whereupon Count Vronsky discovers his lover's lifeless body. Ratmansky's choreography is set to Rodion Shchedrin's music, which is performed by the Mariinsky Orchestra under the baton of Valery Gergiev. Among the dancers are Ulyana Lopatkina, Victor Baranov, Andrei Yermakov, and Svetlana Ivanova. This performance was recorded at the Mariinsky Theatre in St. Petersburg, Russia, in March 2014.

programme.title: Nikolay Lugansky & Vadim Rudenko
programme.sub-title: Piano Duets - Mozart, Ravel, Rachmaninoff a. o.
programme.desc: In this splendid concert, exceptional Russian pianists Nikolay Lugansky and Vadim Rudenko join forces in a program for two pianos comprising works of Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, Maurice Ravel, Anton Arensky, Sergei Rachmaninoff, and Nikolai Kapustin. Both pianists, laureates of the prestigious International Tchaikovsky Competition in 1994, have received international recognition. They perform regularly in a duo. On the program: Mozart's Sonata for two pianos in D major, K. 448/375 A Ravel's La Valse (arr. for two pianos) Arensky's Suite No. 1 for two pianos, Op. 15 and Rachmaninoff's Suite No. 1 (Fantasy) for two pianos, Op. 5. As an encore, the duo performs ‘Romance' from Rachmaninoff's Suite No. 2 for two pianos, Op. 17, followed by ‘Overture' from Nikolai Kapustin's Sinfonietta, Op. 49. This performance was recorded at the Tchaikovsky Concert Hall in Moscow, Russia, on November 25, 2021.

programme.title: David Grimal & Les Dissonances
programme.sub-title: Beethoven - Symphony No. 5 in C minor, Op. 67
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances perform Ludwig van Beethoven's Symphony No. 5 in C minor, Op. 67. Beethoven composed Symphony No. 5 between 1804 and 1808, completing the work at nearly the same time as his Symphony No. 6, ‘Pastorale'. Both symphonies premiered as part of an all-Beethoven program at the same concert on December 22, 1808. Symphony No. 5 has become one of the best-known compositions in classical music. It opens with the famous four-note motif, often interpreted as the musical manifestation of 'fate knocking at the door'. This rhythmic figure returns in various guises in the other three movements of the symphony. The second movement consists of a set of lyrical variations on two themes. The third movement begins gently, but leads to a blasting horn section presenting a theme that features the rhythmic pattern of the four-note motif. The movement leads uninterrupted to the fourth movement that features a triumphant finale ending in C major. This performance was recorded at Philharmonie de Paris, France, in 2015.

programme.title: David Grimal & Les Dissonances
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances play Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart's Violin Concerto No. 4 in D major, K. 218. Leading violinist Grimal features as the soloist. With the exception of the first violin concerto, Mozart composed his other four violin concertos in 1775 at a time when he was concertmaster at the Salzburg court. Among his five concertos, Violin Concerto No. 4 is one of the best-known. This performance was recorded at Cité de la Musique, France, in 2014.

programme.title: Adrien Perruchon, Symfonieorkest Vlaanderen & Josef Špaček
programme.sub-title: Works by Ravel, Lalo, Ginastera a. o.
programme.desc: French conductor Adrien Perruchon and the Flanders Symphony Orchestra take us on a musical journey to Argentine, Spain, and Mexico, in this March 1, 2017 concert performance at Concertgebouw Brugge in Belgium. The program opens with Édouard Lalo's Spanish Symphony for violin and orchestra, Op. 21, featuring Czech violinist Josef Špaček as the soloist. This is followed by Mathias Coppens' Music for Orchestra, Op. 12. The program continues with Alberto Ginastera's Dances from Estancia, Op. 8a, and Aaron Copland's El Salón México. Also on the program is Maurice Ravel's famous Boléro. The program comes to a close with Arturo Márquez's Danzón No. 2.
